    <subfield code="o">36</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">The z-translation operator in outgoing polar null coordinates is ∂z = cos(θ)(∂u - ∂r) - r-1 sin θ∂θ</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">37</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">The out-going null covector in the Bondi-Sachs coordinates is ka = δu a and its optical expansion is ∇aka = (1/r) exp(-2β)</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">38</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Note qA qB γ (1) AB vanishes because γ (1) AB is symmetric and traceless</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">39</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Note there is a phase difference in ref. [15] in the conjugate property (their eq. 2.6) of the sYlm due to another phase convention in the definition of the spherical harmonics</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">40</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">The sYlm are not the only eigenfunctions of ðð, there exist in principle another set of eigenfunctions, sQlm(xA ) say, which are have the property of being irregular at the poles θ ∈ {0, π}</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">41</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">The requirement of a convex normal neighborhood rules out the eigenfunctions sQlm of footnote [40], because they are singular at the poles</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">42</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Bondi, Sachs and collaborators originally studied the asymptotic behavior of the gravitational fields by considering expansions of the metric variables in terms of inverse powers of radial coordinate r</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">43</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">An essential singularity at ˆx = a is ruled out because of the requirement of strict monotonicity. A removable singularity is not allowed because r(ˆx) should have a ’true’ singularity</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">44</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Ref. [35] and Ref. [24], include for numerical purposes a spatial rotation which is not required here</subfield>
  </datafield>
